%I A394906 #20 Apr 14 2026 00:21:34
%S A394906 1,10,2,100,20,1000,110,1001,1010,10000,1100,100000,10010,100001,
%T A394906 100010,1000000,100100,10000000,1000010,10000001,10000010,100000000,
%U A394906 10000100,100000001,100000010,100000002,100000100,1000000000,100001000,10000000000
%N A394906 Representation of n in a positional system with the k-th prime as the k-th place value, choosing the representation that maximizes the decimal value.
%C A394906 Place values are the successive primes in increasing order, with the least significant (rightmost) position valued at 2, the next place to the left valued at 3, then 5,7,11,... For example, the representation 110 equals 1*5 + 1*3 + 0*2 = 8.
%C A394906 For n=10 the possible representations are 1010, 200, 111, 22, and 5; the representation with the largest decimal value is 1010.
%C A394906 The number 1 cannot be represented in this system because the least significant digit has value 2.
%C A394906 If n is the k-th prime, a(n) = 100...0 with k-1 zeros.
%C A394906 The first term with two nonzero digits is a(8)= 110.
%C A394906 The first term with three nonzero digits is a(98) = 100000000000000000001001.
%C A394906 The first term with four nonzero digits is a(370359) = 1(31520 zeros)100000000000000000001001.
%C A394906 Conjecture: For every d > 0 there exists n such that a(n) has exactly d nonzero digits.
%C A394906 Conjecture: a(n) is defined for all n >= 2.
%C A394906 Conjecture: The two least significant (rightmost) digits are in {0,1,2}; all other digits are in {0,1}.
%C A394906 Proof of the first conjecture: If a(n) has m nonzero digits and p > n is a prime such that nextprime(p) > p + n, then a(p + n) has m+1 nonzero digits: a leading digit 1, followed by primepi(p) - length(a(n)) - 1 zeros, followed by the digits of a(n). Since prime gaps are known to become arbitrarily large, such a prime p always exists. - _M. F. Hasler_, Apr 08 2026
%H A394906 David Dewan, <a href="/A394906/b394906.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 2..1000</a>
%H A394906 David Dewan, <a href="/A394906/a394906.pdf">Conjectures Notes for Prime Positional Number System</a>.
%H A394906 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Positional_notation">Positional notation</a>.
%e A394906  n     a(n)    Calculation
%e A394906  2       1     1*2
%e A394906  3      10     1*3
%e A394906  4       2     2*2
%e A394906  5     100     1*5
%e A394906  6      20     2*3
%e A394906  7    1000     1*7
%e A394906  8     110     1*5 + 1*3
%e A394906  9    1001     1*7 + 1*2
%e A394906 10    1010     1*7 + 1*3
%t A394906 a[n_]:=(If[n<2,Return[Nothing]];cur=n;val=0;
%t A394906 While[cur>0,prime=If[PrimeQ[cur],cur,NextPrime[cur,-1]];
%t A394906 If[cur-prime==1,prime=NextPrime[cur,-2]];
%t A394906 cur-=prime;val+=10^(PrimePi[prime]-1)];val);Array[a,31]
%o A394906 (PARI) apply( {A394906(n)=fromdigits([if(n!=p+1, n\p+0*n%=p)|p<-Vecrev(primes([1,n]))])}, [2..50]) \\ _M. F. Hasler_, Apr 08 2026
%Y A394906 Cf. A185101, A007924, A049345.
%K A394906 nonn,base
%O A394906 2,2
%A A394906 _David Dewan_, Apr 06 2026
